Treading with Tunes

A study conducted on the effects of music on one’s walking speed

participants

Two avid enjoyers of various types of music, and frequent walkers. One of us is a lot taller than the other, resulting in more nuanced data. We both recorded each song we listened to while walking, along with each song’s corresponding genre and BPM.

data collection

Data was collected using the iOS Health app for walking speed and stride information, and the Last.fm app for music listening history. We collected data over the course of 2 months.

Lets get some terminology out of the way!

genre

Genre refers to the main category of music. While numerous musical pieces may belong to multiple genres or even have various sub-genres, they typically possess a primary genre that defines their overarching style.

EX: As It Was by Harry Styles - Pop

BPM

BPM, also known as beats per minute, is a measure of how fast the music’s tempo is. The larger the number, song usually have a faster tempo. However, some slow songs have a very fast BPM, this is because when the BPM is too fast, you can sync to half of the BPM.

EX: As It Was by Harry Styles - 174

pace

Pace measures the time it takes to cover a specific distance by walking, expressed in minutes per mile in this data analysis. This metric compares the minutes it takes to walk one mile.

EX: 10’20” - 10 min 20 seconds to complete 1 mile.

stride

Stride refers to the distance between successive steps when walking.

The chart to the right shows the difference between our strides, helping to show that our data has been collected by two very different walkers.

EX: 31.1in

speed

Speed represents the rate at which you can walk over a specified duration. In this data analysis, speed is measured in miles per hour (MPH), indicating the number of miles you can walk within an hour.

EX: 3.6 MPH

genre + bpm mix

Each colored box on this graph shows the distribution of BPM within a specific genre.

Each genre of music has a wide variety of BPM values. Almost all of the genres exhibit great BPM diversity, meaning that there is generally not much of a correlation between BPM and genre.

beat-p-m

Each dot on this chart is a song that we listened to while walking. The songs are color coded by genre.

After collecting data for a couple weeks, we noticed a very evident correlation between walking speed and BPM. The faster the BPM of music we listened to, the quicker we walked.

play-testing

Based off of what we learned from tracking our walking speed with different music, we curated two different playlists with the songs that exhibited the fastest, and slowest walking speeds.

We then listened to these playlists over the next couple weeks to test if they’re the real deal.

taking control!

After listening to our newly created playlists for 2 weeks, there is a noticeable increase that can be seen in the correlation between BPM and walk speed. This means that the playlists that we created were successful in unconsciously manipulating our walking speed through extra fast, or extra slow BPMs.

Thank You!
